iews with the relatives of those whose disappearances remain unsolved; people who were tortured by Turkish paramilitary forces; former soldiers who served in Kurdish cities; researchers, journalists, politicians, lawyers and human rights activists who worked in the region in the 1990sUses court and state documents on Turkish paramilitary forces, as well as secondary sources such as memoirs, journalistic works and NGO reportsThis book focuses on paramilitary groups and the Turkish state relations during the armed conflict between the state and the Kurdistan Workers’ Party (Partiya Karkerên Kurdistan, PKK) in the 1990s. In August 1984, the PKK launched an armed struggle against the Turkish state, leading to a full-blown war throughout the 1990s. During the conflict, the Turkish state established new armed groups, many of them having a paramilitary character. This research investigates the ways in which these paramilitary groups emerged, functioned, and were deactivated. It analyses the historical background, transformations and continuities of these paramilitary groups, and examines their violence against civilians particularly in two regions of Northern Kurdistan: Batman province and Cizre district.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aCounterinsurgencyzTurkey, SoutheasternxHistoryy20th century. 0aParamilitary forceszTurkey, SoutheasternxHistoryy20th century. 0aPolitical violencezTurkey, SoutheasternxHistoryy20th century. 4aIslamic Studies. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 20th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2023 Englishz978311131913108iTitle is part of eBook p